<title>SOUTH AFRICA: Wage talks stall in S.African petroleum sector.</title>
<headline>Wage talks stall in S.African petroleum sector.</headline>
<dateline>CAPE TOWN 1996-09-01</dateline>
<text>
<p>South Africa's petroleum industry said on Sunday talks with the chemical workers' union on wages and working hours had stalled.</p>
<p>&quot;The union rejected a ten percent across the board wage offer and a reduction in average hours worked, taking the maximum in the sector to 43 hours a week,&quot; said a statement by Simon Drysdale, chief negotiator for the petroleum industry.</p>
<p>He said the union wanted shorter hours, a 12 percent across the board increase and a mimimum wage of 1,800 rand a month.</p>
<p>The union had refused to give an undertaking beyond Sunday (September 1) that it would not strike during wage negotiations, Drysdale said.</p>
<p>-- Cape Town newsroom 2721 252238</p>
